      <bioghist id="aspace_358a2418c1d0608c00875328a9d6bf02">
         <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
         <p>Lyman Hale supervised mission schools and churches in Wuhu from 1916 to 1925, and in Nanking from 1925 until evacuated to Shanghai in March 1927. The Hale family resided in Shanghai from 1927 to 1929, with Lyman serving as mission treasurer and secretary. From 1929 Sep to 1941 (except furlough in 1933-1934) the family resided in Chinkiang, with Lyman serving as mission supervisor and treasurer and editor of <title localtype="simple" render="italic">
               <part>The China Christian Advocate</part>
            </title>; served in Nanking after WW II (1945-1949). The Hales twice had their home completely destroyed due to political disturbances (1927 and 1937).</p>  
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_b6e2d2e703d6aaac1a70580c9453d5b9">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>This collection consists primarily of collected material, including valuable typescript and mimeographed accounts of events in China. It contains documentation of 1927 Nanking incident and Japanese occupation 1937-1939, National Christian Council of China Broadcast Bulletins, circular letters from colleagues and friends, correspondence with Methodist mission board, and Chinese language material as well as more than 100 glass slides.</p>  
      </scopecontent>
